1. Introduction

As the years go by, the cost of living has only skyrocketed due to economic inflation. $30,000 was well enough to purchase a house and the many amenities tied to it in the past, but today it is barely enough to scrape by the annual cost of living in many parts of the world, much less the initial down payment for a property. More and more people around the world are struggling to make ends meet as the interest rates continue to rise to account for the inflation, leading to an alarming increase of unemployment rates as well. As college students, we are constantly concerned about the financial strain expenses such as tuition, housing, and dining contributes to the high cost of living. With the surge in lease prices for off-campus housing and grocery costs, we have become particularly aware of how the cost of living can contribute to economic stress in familial households. We aimed to determine the broader impact these fluctuations have throughout the US and globally.

Our datasets include a wide range of economic indicators, including unemployment rates, housing, food, and commodity prices, as well as data reflecting household expenses for varying family sizes. Since our dataset is organized into major cities and countries, we hope to analyze any correlations between geographical location, unemployment, and the overall cost of living, and how these current practices may not be practical or sustainable.

3. Data Exploration/Summary Statistics

Additionally, we noticed that there were a lot of missing values, for rows/cities with missing data, it was typically the whole row. We believe that these cities did not have data as they could be lower income or smaller cities which do not record such data. This data would be categorized as Data Missing Not at Random (NMAR). However, in the context of the dataset, we determined that since this data set seems to include all the cities known in the world, there may be some cities that could not have data collected. Therefore, we realized that it would be impossible to determine these missing values just through the analysis of other cities in the same country due to the variablilty of quality of life and conditions. Thus, as one of our data cleaning steps, we decided to drop rows where no data was collected and only contained NaN values.

However, there were also some countries that were missing only some values, thus for these rows, we decided to utilize the "data quality" column provided in our dataset along to better understand whether or not there was sufficient enough data to keep the row for analysis. Before dropping these values, we also decided to utilize our spliting of data frames into categories to minimize the amount of data loss due to dropping our NaN values.

Analysis of Outliers "Total Cost" of living

To simplify, we wanted to get an overview of our data and see which cities/countries had higher costs of living compared others We decided to drop rows with any NaN values for this section because we were analyzing the "Total Cost" by summing each column (having a NaN would mess with the overall Total Cost). Additionally, since a lot of these rows that contain NaN often have a large quantity of data missing for their columns, we noted that this meant that there was not sufficient data to analyze the city in the first place.

In this code snippet, we decided to create a new feature called Total Costs which would allow us to analyze the overall cost of living for each city. We did this by summing all the values across each city row and thus for purposes of total costs we ended up dropping rows with insufficient data/ NaN values which would interfere with the calculation of Total Cost.

Analyzing Z-Scores

To determine which cities had abnormally high costs of living we decided to use the z-scores and categorize cities into outlier cities (very high costs of living) and non-outlier cities (lower/average costs of living). To do so, we used querying techniques for dataframes to pick out the city names of scores over 2 and under -2 for outliers and between -2 and 2 for regular cities.

In [ ]:
z_score = sp.stats.zscore(outliers_df['Total Costs'], axis = 0)
outliers_df.insert(2, "z-score", z_score)
non_outliers_cities = outliers_df[(outliers_df['z-score'] > (-2)) & (outliers_df['z-score'] < 2)]['City']
outlier_cities = outliers_df[(outliers_df['z-score'] < (-2)) | (outliers_df['z-score'] > 2)]['City']

z_score_df = pd.concat([outliers_df['City'], outliers_df['Total Costs'], outliers_df['z-score']], axis = 1)
z_score_df_outliers = z_score_df[z_score_df['City'].isin(outlier_cities)]

HA: Average Monthly Net Salary has an effect on the cost of a 1 bedroom apartment cost in the city centre

We decided to apply the Man-Whitney U-Test to compare if these two columns were from the same distribution since we were unsure if our data was normally distributed.

In [ ]:
statistic, p_value = sp.stats.mannwhitneyu(hypothesis_test_housing['Average Monthly Net Salary (After Tax)'], hypothesis_test_housing['Apartment 1 bedroom in City Centre'])


print("P-value:", p_value)

P-value: 1.9172555151133802e-192

By using the Man-Whitney U-Test, we found that the p-value was significantly less than the standard alpha value 0.05, thereby disproving the null hypothesis and accept our alternative hypothesis that Average Monthly Net Salary has an effect on the cost of a 1 bedroom apartment cost in the city centre.

As seen in our scatter plot, there seems to be a relatively strong relationship between Net Salary and Housing Costs. We see that relatively, as the amount paid for housing increases, so does the average net salary.

Despite this, we also noted that the proportion at which the housing costs increase is much more drastic compared to the corresponding net salary. This would be something we would want to analyze especially since it tends to be that in some areas where housing costs are high, the net salary is low compared to other areas with cheaper housing costs.

HA: There is at least one category that has a mean that is significantly different from the others.

Data Exploration Conclusions

Through our statistical methods, we were able to reason several strong correlations between the differing categories of living expenses with locations and average salaries. We deduced that there was a strong relationship between average salaries and cost of living within city centres, albeit with some outliers in the form of large cities with abnormally large living costs. We also found the significant different groups within the dataset via ANOVA test and Post-Hoc evaluation, leading us to believe that generally restaurant, market, clothing and miscellaneous costs were connected w/ no significant difference between them, while the other groups like housing, transportation and education had significant differences. In general, there were several outliers and variance because of how drastic living conditions can be in areas with a lower cost of living compared to higher population cities. Because of this we will use implications such as mode or median to ensure that the outliers do not have a substantial effect on our dataset. Finally, due to the size of our dataset it has become apparent that there may have been many other correlations between different columns that we haven't originally considered. Moving forward we will also split the datasets into smaller subsets to more effectively find more focused and detailed analysis.

Here we define lin_model a function that creates a linear regression model and fits our two datasets, outlier and non-outlier cities accordingly. It splits the data into training and testing data for the model to learn on. Then it uses matplotlib, a helpful library for creating visualizations, to plot both graphs side by side. We also calculate the Mean Squared Error (MSE) and the R^2 value to approximate how well our model fits our data. We will want to minimize our MSE and maximize our R^2 value as the closer to 0 our MSE value, and the closer our R^2 value to 1 the better. We will use this model to compare various categories of cost for our dataset.

In [ ]:
def lin_model(X1, y1, X2, y2, x_title):
  X1_train, X1_test, y1_train, y1_test = train_test_split(X1, y1, test_size = 0.2)
  X2_train, X2_test, y2_train, y2_test = train_test_split(X2, y2, test_size = 0.2)

  lm = LinearRegression().fit(X1_train, y1_train)
  predicted = lm.predict(X1_test)

  fig, axs = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(18, 6))

  axs[0].scatter(X1_train, y1_train, color = 'red', label = 'Training Data')
  axs[0].scatter(X1_test, y1_test, color = 'blue', label = 'Testing Data')
  axs[0].plot(X1_test, predicted, color = 'orange', label = 'Linear Regression')
  axs[0].set_xlabel('Average Cost of a ' + x_title + ' in High Cost Living Cities')
  axs[0].set_ylabel('Average Monthly Net Salary (After Tax)')
  axs[0].set_title('Cost of ' + x_title + ' vs Net Salary For High Living Cost Cities')
  axs[0].legend()

  mse = mean_squared_error (y1_test, predicted)
  r2 = r2_score(y1_test, predicted)
  print("Higher Cost Cities:")
  print("MSE: ", mse, "R^2: ", r2)

  lm = LinearRegression().fit(X2_train, y2_train)
  predicted = lm.predict(X2_test)

  axs[1].scatter(X2_train, y2_train, color = 'red', label = 'Training Data')
  axs[1].scatter(X2_test, y2_test, color = 'blue', label = 'Testing Data')
  axs[1].plot(X2_test, predicted, color = 'orange', label = 'Linear Regression')
  axs[1].set_xlabel('Average Cost of a ' + x_title + ' in High Cost Living Cities')
  axs[1].set_ylabel('Average Monthly Net Salary (After Tax)')
  axs[1].set_title('Cost of ' + x_title + ' vs Net Salary for Average Living Cost Cities')
  axs[1].legend()

  mse = mean_squared_error (y2_test, predicted)
  r2 = r2_score(y2_test, predicted)
  print("Average Living Cost Cities:")
  print("MSE: ", mse, "R^2: ", r2)

In our section of exploratory data analysis we found that there were various categories in our datasets that may be from the same distribution. Due to this, we wanted to see if these categories had a similar correlation to average net salary when compared to each other.

As a referesher, we found that food, clothing and other miscelaneous costs were similar and schooling, transportation, and housing were grouped We wanted our main focus of analysis to be on necessities so we picked various features accordingly.

For the upcoming analysis of our datasets, we split our dataset into two categories of cities, high and average living costs, according to the cities that were previously calculated as outliers vs non-outliers.Note that since our outlier dataset is smaller, the regression line is often inaccurate. As a result, the unemployment rates skyrocket from the influx of people who can no longer afford the living costs in areas with high average monthly salary, such as highly-populated cities. It should be noted that the lnear regression model for high living cost cities had a significantly lower R^2 value than the average living cost cities model.

Analyzing Inflation Rates

Inflation is one of the contributing factors to the rising cost of living across the world. Especially when considering that wages do not fluctuate often, increasing inflation rates result in loss of purchasing power for the consumer. When considering the various necessities posed by this data set, we acknowledge that the rise of inflation rates definitely is a concern. Large proportions of salaries often are already allocated to important necessities such as housing, food and clothing. When considering the context of the rising rates, this only puts more of a strain on budgeting for people across the country and all around the world. The following section is an overview and prediction of how inflation has been changing over the years.

For the following section, we decided to incorporate another dataset, "inflation, interest, unemployment.csv". This dataset includes information about inflation, interest and unemployment rates of countries from 1970-2021. We also created the function Polynomial which creates a polynomial regression which can be applied to our dataset to see current trends and produce predictions.

In [ ]:
def Polynomial(X, y, country):

  poly = make_pipeline(PolynomialFeatures(degree =10), LinearRegression()).fit(X, y)
  predicted = poly.predict(X)

  fig, axs = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(18, 6))

  axs[0].scatter(X, y)
  axs[0].set_title('Inflation Rate in the ' + country + ' over time')
  axs[0].set_ylabel('Inflation Rate')
  axs[0].set_xlabel('Year')

  axs[1].scatter(X, y, color = 'red', label = 'Data')
  axs[1].plot(X, predicted, color = 'orange', label = 'Polynomial Regression')
  axs[1].set_title('Inflation Rate in ' + country + ' over time')
  axs[1].set_ylabel('Inflation Rate')
  axs[1].set_xlabel('Year')
  axs[1].legend()

  mse = mean_squared_error (y, predicted)
  r2 = r2_score(y, predicted)
  print("MSE: ", mse, "R^2: ", r2)

  print("Inflation Prediction 2023: ", poly.predict(np.array(2023).reshape(-1,1)))
  print("Inflation Prediction 2025: ", poly.predict(np.array(2025).reshape(-1,1)))

Our second dataset was more difficult to parse, as seen below, rows were categorized by country and year with multiple entries for the same country. As a result, we used the function pivot_table to help create a data frame which would index by country and use years for the columns. The values of the table includes infromation about inflation rates over the years.

Inflation has a significant role on the purchasing power of money, and in turn the overall prices of goods and services over time. As inflation rates increase, so does the currency value in the market, its purchasing power. An increase of inflation results in rising prices for essential goods and services, drastically increasing the overall cost of living per person. In addition, if a person's wages don't account for an increase of inflation, their true income value decreases according to the currency value, further increasing the difficulty for people who already struggling to get by the higher cost of living.

5. Insights and Conclusions

Based on our extensive data analysis and data modeling through linear and polynomial regression,the importance of inflation became ever more apparent. As further predicted by our polynomial regression models, inflation rates throughout several countries have been steadily decreasing since 1970 but show signs of either stabilizing or starting to climb in the past couple of years. Inflation has a significant impact on the cost of living, and as such our models predict that the cost of living may also rise in the next couple years to account for inflation, as the prices for everyday goods and services rise with inflation.

Another evaluation is that certain aspects of living costs have significantly less correlation with average net salary than initially predicted, especially when compared with other necessities. While housing and food costs would drastically increase to account for areas with higher average salaries, clothing costs tended to remain the same cost regardless. This is perhaps due to the fact that clothing costs tend to follow industry pricing and have a stable consumer base willing to meet the costs, while housing and food costs tend to need to change pricings accordingly to maximize sales in different environments.

Most importantly, our models would often generalize the behaviors of an entire country utilizing the averages found in our dataset. While our models provide a good picture of the general behaviors and trends each country may have, it is important to remember that for each average we use, there is an economic disparity that is not properly represented. Our models may effectively find trends to further focus on, but in order to enact real change for the people, it is important to engage in further research on the people whose livelihoods are being directly affected. Each data point has a story behind them, and it is important to acknowledge this in order to better understand and aid the community.
